{"cursor":"23337","size":14,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n or an ellipsoid. The lines from pole to pole are lines of constant longitude,\n or 'meridians'. The circles parallel to the equator are lines of constant\n latitude, or 'parallels'. The graticule determines the latitude and longitude\n of position on the surface.]]\n\n\n\nA 'geographic coordinate system' is a coordinate system that enables every\nlocation on the Earth to be specified by a set of numbers or letters. The\ncoordinates are often chosen such that one of the numbers represents vertical\nposition, and two or three of the numbers represent horizontal position. A\ncommon choice of coordinates is latitude, longitude and elevation. [http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/oswebsite/gps/docs/A_Guide_to_Coordinate_Sys-\ntems_in_Great_Britain.pdf A Guide to coordinate systems in Great Britain] v1.7\nOctober 2007 D00659 accessed 14.4.2008\n","linknr":473,"url":"Geographic_coordinate_system","recorded":1362565400,"links":138,"instances":["graphical","geometry","spherical_coordinates","geodesy","geography"],"pdf":["http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/oswebsite/gps/docs/A_Guide_to_Coordinate_Systems_in_Great_Britain.pdf","http://www.ngs.noaa.gov/PUBS_LIB/Geodesy4Layman/geo4lay.pdf"],"categories":["Geographic coordinate systems|*","Cartography","Navigation","Geodesy","Geocodes"],"headings":["Geographic latitude and longitude","Latitude and longitude in practice","UTM and UPS systems","Stereographic coordinate system","Geodetic height","Cartesian coordinates","Shape of the Earth","Expressing latitude and longitude as linear units","Datums often encountered","Geostationary coordinates","On other celestial bodies","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Sphere_filled_blue.svg/200px-Sphere_filled_blue.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/La